'''Geneticization''' is a term that has been widely used by critics of [[genetic medicine]] since the early 1990s.<ref name=ssm>{{Cite journal |last=Arribas-Ayllon |first=Michael |date=June 2016 |title=After geneticization |url=http://linkinghub.elsevier.com/retrieve/pii/S0277953616302234 |journal=Social Science & Medicine |volume=159 |pages=132–139 |doi=10.1016/j.socscimed.2016.05.011 |issn=0277-9536}}</ref> Originally coined by [[Abby Lippman]] in a series of three papers published in the 1990s (specifically in 1991, 1992, and 1994),<ref name=ssm/> geneticization refers to the increasing tendency to define differences between individuals as largely or entirely due to [[genetics]].<ref>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xLSuP-zmeNkC |title=The Politics of Women's Health: Exploring Agency and Autonomy |last=Sherwin |first=Susan |last2=Network |first2=Feminist Health Care Ethics Research |date=1998 |publisher=Temple University Press |isbn=9781566396332 |pages=64 |language=en}}</ref> This includes the growing framing and understanding of human diseases and behaviors in genetic terms.<ref name=phelan>{{Cite journal |last=Phelan |first=Jo C. |date=December 2005 |title=Geneticization of deviant behavior and consequences for stigma: the case of mental illness |journal=Journal of Health and Social Behavior |volume=46 |issue=4 |pages=307–322 |doi=10.1177/002214650504600401 |issn=0022-1465 |pmid=16433278}}</ref> [[Henk A. M. J. ten Have]] has defined geneticization as "...a [[heuristic]] tool that can help to re-focus the moral debate on the implications of new genetic knowledge towards interpersonal relations, the power of medicine, the cultural context and social constraints, rather than emphasizing issues as personal autonomy and individual rights."<ref>{{Cite journal |last=ten Have |first=Henk A.M.J. |date=2001 |title=Genetics and culture: The geneticization thesis |url=http://link.springer.com/10.1023/A:1012090810798 |journal=Medicine, Health Care and Philosophy |language=en |volume=4 |issue=3 |pages=295–304 |doi=10.1023/a:1012090810798 |issn=1386-7423}}</ref> 

It is common for social scientists and bioethicists to argue that geneticization leads to a growing belief in [[genetic determinism]] and [[essentialism]] in the general public, and that this, in turn, increases [[discrimination]], [[social stigma|stigma]], and [[social inequality|inequality]].<ref name=hedgecoe/><ref name=phelan/> When Lippman originally coined the term "geneticization", for example, she was concerned about the potential for geneticization to increase public belief in biological essentialism, thereby reinforcing racism and discrimination against people with [[disabilities]].<ref>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=myWDPdQFapQC |title=An Anthropology of Biomedicine |last=Lock |first=Margaret |last2=Vinh-kim |first2=Nguyen |last3=Nguyen |first3=Vinh-Kim |date=2010-04-26 |publisher=John Wiley & Sons |isbn=9781405110723 |pages=310 |language=en}}</ref> Some proponents of the heuristic of geneticization also argue that the media's coverage of genetics contributes to geneticization.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Árnason |first=Vilhjálmur |last2=Hjörleifsson |first2=Stefán |date=2007-08-18 |title=Geneticization and bioethics: advancing debate and research |url=http://link.springer.com/10.1007/s11019-007-9088-9 |journal=Medicine, Health Care and Philosophy |language=en |volume=10 |issue=4 |pages=417–431 |doi=10.1007/s11019-007-9088-9 |issn=1386-7423}}</ref> However, the empirical evidence on the link between geneticization and genetic determinism, and between genetic determinism, discrimination and inequality, is ambiguous, suggesting that the phenomenon of geneticization may not always follow the simple pattern that proponents of the concept ascribe to it.<ref name=hedgecoe>{{Cite journal |last=Hedgecoe |first=Adam M |date=2009-12-15 |title=Geneticization: Debates and Controversies |url=http://doi.wiley.com/10.1002/9780470015902.a0005849.pub2 |journal=Encyclopedia of Life Sciences |location=Chichester, UK |publisher=John Wiley & Sons, Ltd |doi=10.1002/9780470015902.a0005849.pub2 |isbn=0470016175}}</ref> 

