{{about|the museum in Stockbridge, Massachusetts|the museum in nearby Pittsfield|Berkshire Museum}} {{Infobox museum | name = Norman Rockwell Museum | native_name = | native_name_lang = | logo = | logo_upright = | logo_alt = | logo_caption = | image = Rockwell museum.jpg | image_upright = 1.35 | alt = | caption = Norman Rockwell Museum main entrance | map_type = | map_relief = | map_size = | map_caption = | coordinates = {{coord|42.2879|-73.3359|type:landmark_region:US-MA|display=inline,title}} | former_name = | established = {{Start date|1993|04|03}} (current building) | dissolved = <!-- {{End date|YYYY|MM|DD|df=y}} --> | location = [[Stockbridge, Massachusetts]] | type = [[Art museum]] | accreditation = | key_holdings = ''[[Four Freedoms (Norman Rockwell)|Four Freedoms]]'', Norman Rockwell Archives | collections = | collection_size = | visitors = | founder = | director = Laurie Norton Moffatt | president = Alice Carter | ceo = | chairperson = | curator = | architect = [[Robert A. M. Stern]] | historian = | owner = | publictransit = | car_park = yes | parking = free parking onsite | network = | website = [http://www.nrm.org/ nrm.org] | embedded = }} The '''Norman Rockwell Museum''' is an [[art museum]] in [[Stockbridge, Massachusetts]], dedicated to the art of [[Norman Rockwell]]. It is home to the world's largest collection of original Rockwell art.
==History== The museum was founded in 1969 in [[Stockbridge, Massachusetts]], where Rockwell lived the last 25 years of his life.<ref name=nrmAbout>{{cite web |url=https://www.nrm.org/about/the-museum/ |title=Museum History |website=nrm.org |accessdate=April 8, 2018}}</ref> Originally located on Main Street in a building known as the Old Corner House,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/19040664/mrs_goulet_director_of_corner_house/ |title=Mrs. Goulet Director of Corner House |newspaper=[[The Berkshire Eagle]] |location=[[Pittsfield, Massachusetts]] |page=20 |date=May 1, 1969 |accessdate=April 8, 2018 |via=newspapers.com}}</ref> the museum moved to its current location 24 years later,<ref name=nrmAbout/> opening to the public on April 3, 1993.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/19040738/simpler_america_gets_fresh_start/ |title=Simpler America Gets Fresh Start |first=Jeff |last=Donn |agency=[[Associated Press|AP]] |newspaper=[[Detroit Free Press]] |page=4 |date=April 3, 1993 |accessdate=April 8, 2018 |via=newspapers.com}}</ref> The current museum building was designed by [[Robert A. M. Stern]].<ref name=nrmAbout/>
==Collection== In addition to 574 original works of art by Rockwell, the museum also houses the Norman Rockwell Archives, a collection of over 100,000 various items, which include photographs, fan mail, and various business documents. In 2014, the [[Famous Artists School]] donated its archives, including process drawings by Rockwell, one of its founding faculty members in 1948, to the museum.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kennedy|first1=Randy|title=The Draw of a Mail-Order Art School: Famous Artists School Archives Go to Norman Rockwell Museum|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/03/23/arts/design/famous-artists-school-archives-go-to-norman-rockwell-museum.html?_r=0|accessdate=23 December 2014|work=New York Times|date=March 20, 2014}}</ref>
[[File:1921-6-4 No Swimming - Norman Rockwell.jpg|thumb|right|''No Swimming'' by Rockwell]] Works by Rockwell at the museum include:<ref>{{cite web |url=http://collections.nrm.org/search.do?db=object&page=1&view=lightbox&highlight=9 |title=Norman Rockwell Painting Collection |website=nrm.org |accessdate=April 7, 2018}}</ref> *''Boy with Baby Carriage'', 1916 *''No Swimming'', 1921 *''[[Four Freedoms (Norman Rockwell)|Four Freedoms]]'', 1943 ** ''[[Freedom from Fear (painting)|Freedom from Fear]]'' ** ''[[Freedom from Want (painting)|Freedom from Want]]'' ** ''[[Freedom of Speech (painting)|Freedom of Speech]]'' ** ''[[Freedom of Worship (painting)|Freedom of Worship]]'' *''Going and Coming'', 1947 *''Christmas Homecoming'', 1948 *''Day in the Life of a Little Girl'', 1952 *''Girl at Mirror'', 1954 *''Art Critic'', 1955 *''Marriage License'', 1955 *''The Runaway'', 1958 *''Family Tree'', 1959 *''[[The Problem We All Live With]]'', 1963 *''The Peace Corps (JFK's Bold Legacy)'', 1966 *''Home for Christmas (Stockbridge Main Street at Christmas)'', 1967
==Awards and grants== [[File:Rockwell studio rear.jpg|thumb|Norman Rockwell's studio]] In 2008, the museum received the [[National Humanities Medal]] from the [[National Endowment for the Humanities]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.neh.gov/about/awards/national-humanities-medals/norman-rockwell-museum |title=Norman Rockwell Museum |website=neh.gov |date=2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/19041151/templeton_foundation_among_us_medal/ |title=Templeton Foundation among U.S. medal winners |first=Bonnie L. |last=Cook |newspaper=[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]] |page=B04 |date=November 18, 2008 |accessdate=April 8, 2018 |via=newspapers.com}}</ref> In 2016, the museum received a grant of $1.5 million from the [[George Lucas]] Family Foundation, which will be used by "the museum's digital learning and engagement division to create multimedia experiences."<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/19041294/rockwell_museum_gets_15m_grant_from/ |title=Rockwell museum gets $1.5M grant from Lucas |newspaper=[[Great Falls Tribune]] |location=[[Great Falls, Montana]] |page=L4 |date=October 4, 2016 |accessdate=April 8, 2018 |via=newspapers.com}}</ref>
