[[File:Ta'liq script 1.jpg|thumb|300px|A Taʿlīq sample]]
The '''taʿlīq script''' (In [[Nastaliq]]: {{lang|fa|{{nq|تعلیق}}}}) is a [[Writing system|script]] style in [[Islamic calligraphy]] designed specifically to satisfy the needs of the [[Persian language]]. It was widely used, especially in [[Persianate society|Persianate societies]], until being replaced by the [[Nastaʿlīq script]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/581497/taliq-script|title=Taʿlīq script - calligraphy|website=www.britannica.com}}</ref> ''Taʿlīq'' is also generally used as the name for the ''[[Nastaʿlīq]]'' script in the Turkish language<ref>{{cite book|last1=Derman|first1=M. Uğur|title=Letters in Gold: Ottoman Calligraphy from the Sakıp Sabancı Collection, Istanbul|date=1998|publisher=Metropolitan Museum of Art|location=New York|isbn=0810965267|page=17}}</ref> and often in the Arabic language.<ref>{{cite book|last1=al-Khattat|first1=Hashim Muhammad|title=Qawa'id al-Khatt al-'Arabi|date=1977|location=Baghdad|page=51}}</ref>The [[Nastaʿlīq script|Nastaliq]] script is also inspired by Ta‘liq.

